cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM, cs.CE

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper focuses on simultaneous wireless information and power transfer (SWIPT) for a multiple-input single-output (MISO) distributed antenna system (DAS) in the downlink. This involves optimizing the power management strategy to maximize wireless information transfer (WIT) while meeting minimum wireless energy transfer (WET) constraints. This falls under the domain of information theory.
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper discusses the use of distributed antenna systems (DAS) in cellular communication systems to cover dead spots and the advantages of DAS in wireless energy transfer (WET). This involves networking and internet architecture aspects of wireless communication systems.
3. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a power management strategy for energy cooperation of energy harvesting (EH) and two-way energy flows to let the remote antenna units (RAUs) trade their harvested energy through the smart grid network. This involves control aspects of the system.
4. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper discusses the performance evaluation of the proposed power management strategy under various settings using simulation results. This involves multimedia aspects of the system.
5. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The paper involves optimization of the power management strategy to maximize WIT while meeting minimum WET constraints. This involves computational engineering aspects of the system.
